<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n08179a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08179a">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08179a"> 179(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> poet split in three / = chronicler, poet, brehon</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Another cause of their <font color="green">[the poets&apos;]</font> importance was that they transmitted the law that is to say, the judgments which from time to time were delivered by the kings. So it became natural that before a king or ruler gave judgment he should consult the living record of what had been decided in previous cases; and thus the learned in poetry and history became recognised also as authorities upon law and advisers upon judgment. <small> Stephen Gwynn, <a name="SGHI" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SGHI"><cite title="source">The History of Ireland</cite></a> (1923) 11</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
